book119 = Book.create({ title: "Palm Trees in the Snow", author: "Luz Gabs", image_url: "https://res.cloudinary.com/dt72mzjpx/image/upload/book_119.jpg", publisher: "AmazonCrossing ", date: "February 1, 2017", description: " At once an epic family drama and a sweeping love story that spans both an ocean and a generation, Palm Trees in the Snow is an emotionally gripping and historically vivid tale of the secrets that can destroy a family&#x2014;and the bonds that endure.When Clarence of Rabaltu&#xe9; discovers a series of old letters from her father&#x2019;s past, she begins to doubt everything she thought she knew about her once-noble family. Her father and his brother worked in the colony of Fernando Po, but these letters tell a different story than the tales of life in Africa that made it to the dinner table. Clarence has no idea what really went on during their time at the cocoa plantations&#x2014;or why no one in her family has ever returned to the island in all the years since. But the letters suggest that a great love story is buried beneath the years of silence.Setting out from her home in Spain&#x2019;s snowy mountains, Clarence makes the same journey across the sea that her uncle and father traveled before her. There, she unlocks the painful secrets her family has hidden in the rich African soil. But what she discovers may also be the key to awakening her own listless heart.", amazon_link: "https://www.amazon.com/Palm-Trees-Snow-Luz-Gab%C3%A1s-ebook/dp/B01HIHWU6E", kobo_link: "https://www.kobo.com/us/en/search?query=Palm%20Trees%20in%20the%20Snow%20Luz%20Gab%C3%A1s", play_link: "https://play.google.com/store/search?c=books&hl=en&q=Palm%20Trees%20in%20the%20Snow%20Luz%20Gab%C3%A1s" })
Review.create({ title: "Eureka! A true treasure!", rating: 5, body: "How refreshing to be able to choose a Kindle monthly book with such quality and breadth! Palm Trees in the Snow is a true saga of the kind that is so seldom now attempted by scholars with a story to tell. The depth of characters and plot make it possible to settle into the story for true enjoyment and be rewarded also with a history that it's unlikely current readers would have sought on their own. An unexpected perk is the revelation at the end of the story that all relationships aren't as they would seem.  Nice surprise.A totally enjoyable read.!", user_id: user1.id, book_id: book119.id })
Review.create({ title: "Having a linguistics lecturer as a main character added good depth and the mysterious letter at the beginning was ...", rating: 4, body: "Thanks to this dramatic and engaging novel, I now have appreciation for a country I previously knew only in name: Equatorial Guinea. As a longtime fan of historically-based novels, I found Palm Trees full of passion and struggle and warmth. Having a linguistics lecturer as a main character added good depth and the mysterious letter at the beginning was a good hook. There are two reasons I give it four stars instead of five.1. Too many minor characters are spread way too thin. Too many people (Regina, Nelson, Boseupo, and others) are mentioned early in the book and then not again for 300 or 400 pages. Too many characters diluted the main story.2. The romance aspect of the novel was overdone for my tastes: Both had been with others, but they had never entrusted their souls to anyone. Now they did. Meh.If you enjoy novels set in times of political, economic, and racial turmoil, with interwoven family sagas (and a lot of romance), then give this a try.", user_id: user2.id, book_id: book119.id })
Review.create({ title: "Great Human Story", rating: 5, body: "Very interesting story about relations between Equatorial Guinea and Spain towards the end of colonial times and thereafter (or to be exact between Guineans and Spaniards) and the effects of colonialism on both countries long after the practice has ended. I found the story captivating, with well-developed characters we follow throughout their lifetime, and enough twists and turns to keep the reader interested. I did not know much about Guinea and learned a lot about its recent history and colonial past. This selection may be a little different and a bit more challenging than the usual books offered on Kindle First but I would recommend it to anyone interested in learning more about less well-known parts of the world and not intimidated by a more complex story line.", user_id: user3.id, book_id: book119.id })
Review.create({ title: "I have learned much but not enough", rating: 5, body: "This is a wonderful novel that though fictional is so deeply grounded in truths it could also be biographical. The years of Spain's colonization of  Guinea are told from the points of view of the people of Guinea, the imported workers and plantation owners from Spain who had managerial roles and the laborers from Nigeria and other countries. It is both a poignant and painful read. The inhumane and bigoted parts are difficult to read. The love and respect that grew among others gave you hope. The hardest part was even after Spain backed a democracy the new rulers were brutal toward smaller tribes and factions within their own country. It seems we never learn that war and hatred of people with different view points is wrong. The love story imbedded within all of the political intrigue was beautiful but sad and the discoveries made by the children were deeply moving. Not an easy book but I am better and a little wiser after reading it. This author has a true gift of bringing you into the story and making the emotions and realizations come to life.", user_id: user4.id, book_id: book119.id })
Review.create({ title: "Delight saga", rating: 4, body: "Very enjoyable, well researched historical novel.  The plot was intriguing:  the story was told via two different generations, the latter one discovering family details long hidden by the former.  The major characters were mostly well drawn, and there were lots of them from two major cultures.  The setting covered two continents and over 50 years.  Palm Trees in the Snow is a lengthy saga, but at the same time a real page turner.  I am glad I started it just before an ice storm hit so I had an excuse to read it in just a couple of days!", user_id: user5.id, book_id: book119.id })
Review.create({ title: "Quite A Novel", rating: 4, body: "Picked this book as my January First Book Selection.  Turned out to be quite a book.  Think that all the emotions were covered by the various characters.  Some characters were very likeable, some were definitely hard to warm up to.  All in all though they were all very complex.  I am not usually a history buff but did find this time period interesting.  Found that some sections seemed to drag usually in the spaces about the history which tried to put a lot in to one place.  The storyline was complex, as the characters were, loved the romance storyline especially with enduring love.  It was a long book but I actually enjoyed it for the most part.", user_id: user6.id, book_id: book119.id })
Review.create({ title: "A story of two worlds", rating: 4, body: "An excellent book that is both well written and intriguing. Its story lines are interwoven through time in the past and the present and place in the two distinctly different worlds of Spain and Colonial Guinea.  Throughout the book, the complexity of romantic and family relationships are explored with beautiful depth. There is no perfect character, no shining hero or heroine, just realistic full-bodied people who live and love in the best way they can.", user_id: user7.id, book_id: book119.id })
book120 = Book.create({ title: "Girl JackedAuthor: Christopher GreysonGenre: mysteryReview:Girl Jacked, written by, revolved around a policeman named Jack. After discovering that the sister of his best friend from high school had gone missing, he is determined to take this case into his own hands. However, before he knows it, the mystery of the death of the missing girl has gotten him into a web of entangled lies and malice.I liked the main character, Jack, a lot.  There’s really no reason not to like him.  He’s tough, he’s smart, determined and has a strong sense of ethics. However, he also experienced flashbacks of his time serving in the military. I found them to be insightul and help paint a better picture of his character. Also, I think the author did an excellent job of summing up Jack;s early years as a child in the scene in which Jack explains why he named himself Jack. Over all, Jack was a solidly built character.Replacement (the name of the missing girl’s sister), on the other hand, was more of a wild card. Replacement’s real name is Alice, but everyone calls her Replacement, so that is the name I will use.  She approaches Jack, seeking help to solve her missing sister’s case.  Even though she’s supposed to be a young adult (early twenties?), she often acts like a twelve-year old.  I got frustrated with her when she purposely disobeys Jack and ends up getting in trouble.  I mean, I would’ve understood it if she ignored his orders once or twice, but the fact that she repeatedly took the opposite course of action of what Jack advised kind of annoyed me.  Why should she seek help from Jack if she wasn’t going to listen to him?At the beginning, the plot seemed like a simple missing-person mystery. However, 33% into the book, readers quickly discover that the missing-person case has turned into a murder mystery.  In short, what seemed like a basic story line actually unfolds into a more complex tale, which I enjoyed.The writing overall was good and very readabl