book123 = Book.create({ title: "Life and Other Near-Death Experiences", author: "Camille Pagn", image_url: "https://res.cloudinary.com/dt72mzjpx/image/upload/book_123.jpg", publisher: "Lake Union Publishing ", date: "November 1, 2015", description: " Libby Miller has always been an unwavering optimist&#x2014;but when her husband drops a bomb on their marriage the same day a doctor delivers devastating news, she realizes her rose-colored glasses have actually been blinding her.With nothing left to lose, she abandons her life in Chicago for the clear waters and bright beaches of the Caribbean for what might be her last hurrah. Despite her new sunny locale, her plans go awry when she finds that she can&#x2019;t quite outrun the past or bring herself to face an unknowable future. Every day of tropical bliss may be an invitation to disaster, but with her twin brother on her trail and a new relationship on the horizon, Libby is determined to forget about fate. Will she risk it all to live&#x2014;and love&#x2014;a little longer?From critically acclaimed author Camille Pag&#xe1;n comes a hilarious and hopeful story about a woman choosing between a &#x201c;perfect&#x201d; life and actually living.", amazon_link: "https://www.amazon.com/Other-Near-Death-Experiences-Camille-Pag%C3%A1n-ebook/dp/B00U6IQFFU", kobo_link: "https://www.kobo.com/us/en/search?query=Life%20and%20Other%20Near-Death%20Experiences%20Camille%20Pag%C3%A1n", play_link: "https://play.google.com/store/search?c=books&hl=en&q=Life%20and%20Other%20Near-Death%20Experiences%20Camille%20Pag%C3%A1n" })
Review.create({ title: "Hooked me", rating: 5, body: "Have you ever started to read a book, and from the first few pages you could tell it was going to hook you?  That was this book for me.  I chose it as my October early-release freebie through Prime.  The same day I ordered this, I downloaded about 4 other books through my public library.  I was going to read a few pages from each book and see which grabbed my attention.  I started with this book and just kept reading.It was well written and well edited.  Witty humor was interjected throughout, and while centered around a deep subject, the book was light and yes, maybe a bit fluffy. I felt that the main characters were well developed and part of what kept me hooked was that I cared about Libby and wanted to see what happened to her.  I appreciate that this was a &#34;clean&#34; book - no swearing, no explicit sex scenes, but I would have liked Libby's first love scene to have been slightly more detailed.  At only a sentence or two long, at first I wasn't sure if it was something that had actually happened.I disagree with what one reviewer said about everything being neatly tied up in a bow at the end. Not everything with Libby was tied up at the end of the book -which I found surprisingly unpredictable.  Yes, there was a happy ending of course - and I would not have wanted it any other way.(Getting an early release copy through Prime is in no way tied to a promise of writing a review.)", user_id: user1.id, book_id: book123.id })
Review.create({ title: "AN EASY  READ -- upbeat  novel of REAL LIFE'S CHALLENGES", rating: 5, body: "", user_id: user2.id, book_id: book123.id })
Review.create({ title: "Worth reading but...", rating: 4, body: "I chose this as my October Kindle First selection.  I've been a avid reader of nearly every genre, from fluff to serious novels all my life, but one thing I can't stand is poor writing.  I've given up on many, many books because the author just couldn't cobble together more than a few good sentences or had a decent first couple of chapters then went awry, especially in this day of e-publishing.  Fortunately this is not one of those books.The premise was ok, the writing was ok, the book kept my attention for the entire evening it took to read, but I had problems with some of the main character's actions, especially related to her (soon to be) ex-husband's reveal.  And especially in the light of her twin brother's situation.  My other problem with this book was how everything was neatly tied in a bow in the end.But if you can't find a fluffy book that holds your attention, I'd recommend this.  It's good enough.", user_id: user3.id, book_id: book123.id })
Review.create({ title: "Not the best, not the worst", rating: 3, body: "This is a fluffy read about a women who's diagnosed with cancer and decides to go have one last hurrah before dying. Other reviewers have covered the plotline pretty well. The plot itself isn't bad, but I get annoyed when authors make mistakes in the details of their story. Some examples:1. When Libby first arrives in Vieques, her luggage is left on the plane while she drives to her beach cottage. At the beach cottage, she suddenly now has her luggage in the car, but is too tired to take it inside so she leaves it there. Then a few pages later, the pilot shows up with her luggage.2. Libby and Shiloh go kayaking, which Libby is worried about because she's not athletic. Shiloh hands Libby a kayak, proving to me that obviously the author has never had anything to do with kayaks. How do you &#34;hand&#34; somebody a 10-foot-long boat? Those things are seriously unweildy to cart around, but non-athletic Libby takes hers to the ocean with no problem. While kayaking, Libby hops out of the kayak and swims around before getting back into the kayak. Now, I own a kayak, and I'm very athletic, and it takes a heck of a lot of skill to climb back into a kayak from the water. If I can't do it, I highly doubt Libby could.I found the author's flippant and snarky perspective of cancer to be offensive. I was shocked at the end to read her statement about how cancer has affected many of her friends and family, and that she wanted to be respectful in how she dealt with it. I guess she was trying to match the light-heartedly fluffy tone of the book and deal with cancer in a light-hearted and fluffy way, but it really rubbed me the wrong way. And I have had cancer. Also, I get that Libby was dying and wanted to live her life, but her determination to have sex with somebody else besides her husband was very off-putting. Basically the first thing she did after her diagnosis was try to hook up with a co-worker. When that didn't work out, oh hey here's this dude in Puerto Rico that I have nothing in common with, except he's horny too. Talk about a rebound man- Shiloh was a disgusting love interest. The guy wears the same nasty shorts and shirts for days in a sweaty tropical climate?The author did have some clever expressions and funny ways of wording things so it wasn't a total loss.", user_id: user4.id, book_id: book123.id })
book124 = Book.create({ title: "The Last Girl (The Dominion Trilogy Book 1)", author: "Joe Hart", image_url: "https://res.cloudinary.com/dt72mzjpx/image/upload/book_124.jpg", publisher: "Thomas & Mercer ", date: "March 1, 2016", description: " From Wall Street Journal bestselling author Joe Hart.A mysterious worldwide epidemic reduces the birthrate of female infants from 50 percent to less than 1 percent. Medical science and governments around the world scramble in an effort to solve the problem, but twenty-five years later there is no cure, and an entire generation grows up with a population of fewer than a thousand women.Zoey and some of the surviving young women are housed in a scientific research compound dedicated to determining the cause. For two decades, she&#x2019;s been isolated from her family, treated as a test subject, and locked away&#x2014;told only that the virus has wiped out the rest of the world&#x2019;s population.Captivity is the only life Zoey has ever known, and escaping her heavily armed captors is no easy task, but she&#x2019;s determined to leave before she is subjected to the next round of tests&#x2026;a program that no other woman has ever returned from. Even if she&#x2019;s successful, Zoey has no idea what she&#x2019;ll encounter in the strange new world beyond the facility&#x2019;s walls. Winning her freedom will take brutality she never imagined she possessed, as well as all her strength and cunning&#x2014;but Zoey is ready for war.", amazon_link: "https://www.amazon.com/Last-Girl-Dominion-Trilogy-Book-ebook/dp/B011UNEZN8", kobo_link: "https://www.kobo.com/us/en/search?query=The%20Last%20Girl%20(The%20Dominion%20Trilogy%20Book%201)%20Joe%20Hart", play_link: "https://play.google.com/store/search?c=books&hl=en&q=The%20Last%20Girl%20(The%20Dominion%20Trilogy%20Book%201)%20Joe%20Hart" })
Review.create({ title: "Loved it!", rating: 5, body: "Wow, I'm surprised at how many negative reviews.  This goes to show me that I can't judge a book based off other's opinions as I loved this book.  I thought he did well with the character building and the plot.  The story line was unique and intriguing.  I was sucked in very quickly and didn't put the put down until it was finished.  Was it perfect?  No.  Did it sweep me away into his imagination and take me to another world?  Yes, it did and I was on the edge of my seat reading it at times waiting for what happens next.  I will buy the next book in the series.  I'm hooked!  Excellent job, Joe Hart.  I've found a new author!", user_id: user1.id, book_id: book124.id })
Review.create({ title: "Several problems, from pacing to character development.", rating: 2, body: "This review contains some spoilers, but those are at the end, and clearly marked. I read this as part of Kindle First.This novel contains profanity, violence, and instances of non-graphic, attempted non-consensual sexual content (attempted rape). The violence is mostly plot relevant, however the sexual content is gratuitous in nature, and the novel suffered for it.The premise of this novel--dystopian society, low birth rates, fertile women treated as property--reminds me somewhat of 'The Handmaid's Tale' (Margaret Atwood). Unfortunately, in all of the places where Atwood's novel succeeds, 'The Last Girl' fails.I only give novels which I can't finish a single star, but this one came close to making me break that rule. There's so much 'I don't like this' going on that I'm not sure where to start.Characters: mostly not developed. The villains are all disfigured, or easily recognizable by their sneers/general sliminess, and their motives make Snidely Whiplash's look complex. The secondary characters aren't memorable. The main character is just like any other female dystopian main character--she's spunky, can get pummeled on the regular and bounce back, handles a firearm well (despite only having seen them in holsters, on guards), etc, etc.Plot: 'Spunky girl fights evil dystopian establishment,' with a side of attempted rape, and bizarre cruelty toward the other young girls in the story. Far too much reliance on tropes, cliches, and archetypes to create 'twists' to move the plot.Writing style: okay. It's not 'pretty,' but it's mostly serviceable, without too much dry, clunky phrasing.Pacing: Very inconsistent. Far too much exposition. Much of the world-building is done in the form of characters reading in classroom lessons. (For comparison, 'The Girl with All the Gifts' does this brilliantly.)Overall, I wouldn't recommend this. If the premise of this book interests you, I would recommend 'The Handmaid's Tale.'***spoilers beyond this point*******There are so many things that didn't make sense to me in this story. Here are just a few.Why were the girls treated so poorly? It makes zero logical sense, other than causing the main character angst.Why bother such an elaborate system of lying to these girls? Their compliance was guaranteed regardless. It seems contradictory, given that the reader is told (repeatedly) how little the powers that be care for the girls.Why bother keeping the sperm donors around the facility?Regarding the abusive guard...If women are so precious, surely they wouldn't keep a guard around with a history of inappropriate contact.What purpose did Lily, the handicapped girl, serve? I was initially pleasantly surprised to see a handicapped character in this story. Unfortunately, it seems her inclusion is only to cause more angst for the main character.Last...I can't buy into the government slaughtering the bulk of the population. A country, torn by unrest, with its infrastructure going to pieces, finances in the toilet, somehow manages to coordinate and fund the slaughter and disposal of 300 million people? They convince their military (composed of citizens) this is the best course? Sorry, I can' t get on board that train.", user_id: user2.id, book_id: book124.id })
