Review.create({ title: "Strangely engaging - but such a disappointment", rating: 1, body: "Have you ever read a book and been like, what made me read that? I mean sure it was free because of my Amazon Prime membership - but what kept me reading it until the very end? I guess I wanted to know what happened to Zoey (the lead character). Though I can say that this book was a colossal disappointment and waste of time. POSSIBLE SPOILERS -- QUIT READING NOW -- SPOILERS. I think I have to tell you a little bit about the book to let you know why I am so disappointed in it. There are just things that don't make sense. Like if girl babies, can't be born anymore why are the girls treated so poorly? And if women are so few and valuable - why do they keep getting rid of the women like they have no value? How impossible is it that Zoey - who gets an hour of exercise a day - and has lived a sheltered life suddenly knows how to shoot a gun, and can defeat attacker after attacker and still prevail? Her hatred is what gives her super powers? Anyway  - you may heed this warning - or you may not - but I promise you this book will disappoint you.", user_id: user4.id, book_id: book124.id })
book126 = Book.create({ title: "Small Great Things: A Novel", author: "Jodi Picoult", image_url: "https://res.cloudinary.com/dt72mzjpx/image/upload/book_126.jpg", publisher: "Ballantine Books ", date: "October 11, 2016", description: " #1 NEW YORK TIMES BESTSELLER &bull; With richly layered characters and a gripping moral dilemma that will lead readers to question everything they know about privilege, power, and race, Small Great Things is the stunning new page-turner from&#160;Jodi Picoult. &ldquo;[Picoult] offers a thought-provoking examination of racism in America today, both overt and subtle. Her many readers will find much to discuss in the pages of this topical, moving book.&rdquo;&mdash;Booklist (starred review) Ruth Jefferson is a labor and delivery nurse at a Connecticut hospital with more than twenty years&rsquo; experience. During her shift, Ruth begins a routine checkup on a newborn, only to be told a few minutes later that she&rsquo;s been reassigned to another patient. The parents are white supremacists and don&rsquo;t want Ruth, who is African American, to touch their child. The hospital complies with their request, but the next day, the baby goes into cardiac distress while Ruth is alone in the nursery. Does she obey orders or does she intervene? Ruth hesitates before performing CPR and, as a result, is charged with a serious crime. Kennedy McQuarrie, a white public defender, takes her case but gives unexpected advice: Kennedy insists that mentioning race in the courtroom is not a winning strategy. Conflicted by Kennedy&rsquo;s counsel, Ruth tries to keep life as normal as possible for her family&mdash;especially her teenage son&mdash;as the case becomes a media sensation. As the trial moves forward, Ruth and Kennedy must gain each other&rsquo;s trust, and come to see that what they&rsquo;ve been taught their whole lives about others&mdash;and themselves&mdash;might be wrong. With incredible empathy, intelligence, and candor, Jodi Picoult tackles race, privilege, prejudice, justice, and compassion&mdash;and doesn&rsquo;t offer easy answers. Small Great Things is a remarkable achievement from a writer at the top of her game.Praise for Small Great Things&ldquo;Small Great Things is the most important novel Jodi Picoult has ever written. . . . It will challenge her readers . . . [and] expand our cultural conversation about race and prejudice.&rdquo;&mdash;The Washington Post &ldquo;A novel that puts its finger on the very pulse of the nation that we live in today . . . a fantastic read from beginning to end, as can always be expected from Picoult, this novel maintains a steady, page-turning pace that makes it hard for readers to put down.&rdquo;&mdash;San Francisco Book Review &ldquo;A gripping courtroom drama . . . Given the current political climate it is quite prescient and worthwhile. . . . This is a writer who understands her characters inside and out.&rdquo;&mdash;Roxane Gay, The New York Times Book Review&ldquo;I couldn&rsquo;t put it down. Her best yet!&rdquo;&mdash;New York Times&#160;bestselling author Alice Hoffman&ldquo;A compelling, can&rsquo;t-put-it-down drama with a trademark [Jodi] Picoult twist.&rdquo;&mdash;Good Housekeeping&ldquo;It&rsquo;s Jodi Picoult, the prime provider of literary soul food. This riveting drama is sure to be supremely satisfying and a bravely thought-provoking tale on the dangers of prejudice.&rdquo;&mdash;Redbook&ldquo;Jodi Picoult is never afraid to take on hot topics, and in&#160;Small Great Things, she tackles race and discrimination in a way that will grab hold of you and refuse to let you go. . . . This page-turner is perfect for book clubs.&rdquo;&mdash;Popsugar&#160;", amazon_link: "https://www.amazon.com/Small-Great-Things-Jodi-Picoult-ebook/dp/B01AQNYZ3I", kobo_link: "https://www.kobo.com/us/en/search?query=Small%20Great%20Things:%20A%20Novel%20Jodi%20Picoult", play_link: "https://play.google.com/store/search?c=books&hl=en&q=Small%20Great%20Things:%20A%20Novel%20Jodi%20Picoult" })
Review.create({ title: "I saw myself in this story", rating: 5, body: "As a &#34;successful middle-class&#34; African-American woman I was truly stunned to recognize so many aspects of my own life in Ruth.  I have read every Picoult book - some twice - but never have I had my own experiences articulated so effectively by someone who isn't a person of color.  I finished it yesterday morning and was rattled all day by the insights and depth of honesty revealed here.  I still am, but had to take a moment to post everywhere and say THANK YOU!!  Jodi, I read your acknowledgments of how you created this book, and I wish I could meet you.  I am awed and will recommend this book to anyone I know:  starting with my husband.  Blessings to you for your courage, research and determination to see beyond what you knew, what was comfortable - and take this risk.", user_id: user1.id, book_id: book126.id })
Review.create({ title: "MLK remembered", rating: 5, body: "Finished this book on MLK Day.....How appropriate a day to continue my  journey toward increased self awareness.  Excellent read!  Highly recommend", user_id: user2.id, book_id: book126.id })
Review.create({ title: "Tight-lipped, Kennedy nods. You're right. I don't know what it's like to be black.", rating: 3, body: "&#34;Small Great Things&#34; is uncomfortable. Not in a way that I'm learning a long overdue lesson. But in the way embarrassment and anger course through your body when a younger sibling repeats every word out of your mouth, in squeaking-pitched tone and screwed up face. Mockingly, everything sounds familiar, but it's not real.Picoult notes, maybe too late, that she &#34;[was] writing to my own community&#8212;white people&#8212;who can very easily point out a Neo-Nazi skinhead...but who can't recognize racism in themselves.&#34;As a Black woman, part of me wrestled with what gave Picoult trhe right to contribute to our narrative? To tell our struggles? To tell the world what it feels like in Black skin to deal with overt racism to passing microagressions? I quickly let go of those questions because Picoult never does any of that. Every page, dripping with white guilt, is the perception of what someone thinks Black life is. The novel is rife with stereotypes, a dichotomy between Ruth and her sister of a &#34;good Black&#34; and a &#34;Bad Black&#34; that I'm not sure even Picoult understands. Basic cultural cues watered down until its lossed its meaning. It's all too much of a reminder that indeed, Picoult does not know what it feels like to be Black.Funny, to me the only relatable character became the white supremacist. In his few chapters, you understand abandonment, loss, love, betrayal, anger and grief. Beyond race, gender and class you could understand his emotions, motivations and actions, albeit sometimes off character. But maybe that was Picoult's plan all along&#8212;to create sympathy for those unlike ourselves.  But, even so, this well-intentioned book misses the mark.", user_id: user3.id, book_id: book126.id })
