book161 = Book.create({ title: "Friction", author: "", image_url: "https://res.cloudinary.com/dt72mzjpx/image/upload/book_161.jpg", publisher: "HEA Press, LLC ", date: "January 16, 2017", description: " A new standalone romance from NYTimes and USA Today Bestselling Author, Emily SnowFormer overachiever Lucy WillIams sucks at adulting. Recent divorce, check. Pending lawsuit, check. A move back to Boston to live with her mother, triple check. It can't get much worse, right? When she starts her new marketing job at EXtreme Effects, she's positive shit&#x2019;s stopped hitting the fan. Sure, what she's advertising is a little ... unorthodox, but it pays the bills. And since she's seconds away from becoming Lucy Williams: Wednesday Night Bingo Enthusiast, she needs money to get the hell out of her mother&#x2019;s house. The only problem is her boss, Mr. Extreme himself: Jace Exley. He&#x2019;s everything any sane woman dreams of&#x2014;alpha, successful, ridiculously gorgeous. He's also Lucy&#x2019;s worst nightmare. Because like every overachiever, she has that underachiever she brushed off. The slacker who, once upon a time ago, was the object of her dirtiest schoolgirl fantasies. Jace Exley&#x2014;with his sarcastic smirk and delicious accent&#x2014;just happens to be that guy. And the friction between them? Well, that's the only adulting Lucy seems to be winning at", amazon_link: "https://www.amazon.com/Friction-Emily-Snow-ebook/dp/B01MS8HDZ5", kobo_link: "https://www.kobo.com/us/en/search?query=Friction%20", play_link: "https://play.google.com/store/books/details/Sandra_Brown_Sunset_Embrace?id=r5UzOxOEsfsC" })
Review.create({ title: "Im in lust with Jace Exley!", rating: 4, body: "Ive seen that look enough times to know what thoughts were rolling through that brilliant mind of yours. You were curious. And curiosity is a beautiful thing. Despite the saying, it really didnt kill the pussy.Wow! Talk about SEXUAL TENSION..Friction is full of itI LOVED IT!!!!Lucy finds herself in a situation shed rather not be in..her ex-husband and boss is job blocking her after she catches him in a compromising position with a co-worker and decides to leave the company and file for divorce. Now she finds herself moving back home and living with her mother.After getting door after door slammed in her face job wise shes desperate and decides to accept an interview for a job she found on craigslist. Little does she know the job comes with a blast from the past.Jace and Lucyi really enjoyed their story and the high amounts of tension that came with it. This is a novel where you seriously try to predict what is going to happen next but come up wrong every single time.I loved the endless banter between Lucy and Jace. I loved how Lucy was a spitfire ready with a comeback to Jaces remarks. I also loved the fact that Jace and Lucy were enemies in high school but secretly lusted after each other and even through the years of not being in each others lives that never went away.Im in lust with Jace Exley and hisbusiness!Friction is definitely worthy of a re-read and a 1-click!", user_id: user1.id, book_id: book161.id })
Review.create({ title: "I did NOT want this book to end", rating: 5, body: "Friction is the 1st book Ive read by Emily Snow. I need to be completely honest  I did NOT want this book to end, I was actually a little sad reading the epilogue. Not because it was sad  but because I wanted Lucy and Jaces story to continue. From the first chapter, hell the first sentence, I was hooked  I couldnt put this book down.Lucy  shes a prude, marketing agent. She recently moved back to her hometown of Worcester, MA. near Boston, after things went downhill ( to put it mildly) in San Fran.  Shes on a hunt for a new job, problem is  her previous employer isnt giving her rave reviews.  She applies for a job from Craigslist, after her mom insists that she bring mace with her to the interview (LOL)  shes on her way.  What she doesnt expect ( but we do because come on  its a romance novel!)  is to make eye contact with her high school obsession.  Things are never as they seem and Lucy learns this extremely quickly. Jace  wow, he grabs hold of you with his possessiveness and doesnt let Lucy OR you go!The humor, the angst, the feelings, the sex  this story  JUST WOW! The humor, quite honestly is what grabbed hold of me.I am already looking for other books by Ms. Snow to entertain my imagination.5 Stars from me. I received a complimentary copy of this book in exchange for a honest opinion.", user_id: user2.id, book_id: book161.id })
Review.create({ title: "5 Higly Entertaining Stars", rating: 5, body: "Meet Lucy Williams, freshly divorced, cheated on by her ex-husband, looking for a job, living with her mother and an overachiever.Called Lucy-I-****ing-Know-Everything-Williams.(I'm very sorry but A. let me not post this word)And Jace Exel , a successful business owner.His rule: No relationships with employees.Both have this crazy chemistry and fight against.But to no avail.This novel is a great read. It is fast, full of twists and turns and I couldn't put it down.This book cost me a whole nights sleep. And I'm not sorry.I highly recommend Friction.5 Stars and Thank you Emily Snow !!", user_id: user3.id, book_id: book161.id })
Review.create({ title: "Sexy, Funny & Entertaining", rating: 5, body: "4.5 StarsIf I had to sum the book up in only one word, I would say it was entertaining.Lucy is one of lifes winners, that is right up until the point where the rug was proverbially pulled from right beneath her because not only did she lose her marriageher ex was a cheating SOB ( and later in the story you will find out just what an a$$ he really is) so in the scheme of things that might not have been a huge issue but he was also her business partner and that is a major issue because now she has no relationship, no job and is facing whole heap of personal and professional painall topped off by the fact that she is now living with her mom againlife is far from peachy!Finding a job that she isnt actually overqualified for isnt easy but eventually she is hired for a company that is owned by a guy that she had a major thing for back in high school. Now I dont know about you but I think I might have found that almost as awkward as she did and that is saying something!She had no idea what was coming her way when she accepted that job but then again I dont think Jace did either because when she walked back into his life again it was as if he was right back in high school because Lucy wasnt the only one that had harboured a secret crush.Sexy as sin Jace was on very thin ice when it came to offering Lucy the position as his marketing director, he had rules for how things should be between staff and that included him but all that was before L.E.T.O (Lucy Entered The Office) because now he may just be the one breaking that very same rule.I loved his attitude, he called it like he saw it and wasnt afraid to say exactly what was on his mind, Lucy on the other hand had a rod of steel running through her because no matter how down, how despondent you would have thought she would be, she soldiered on and what she didnt initially overcome she buried but Jace knew that he was there to help her find that tiger again, to see through the BS, start again and stand tall.The interaction between the two of them were mixed, they were playful, they were flirtatious, they were sexy and eventually they were off the charts! They brought out the best in each other and that was fantastic to read.It isnt all plain sailing there is a hiccup along the way ( I did mention that ex earlier) that had the potential to derail everything for them both and again not just personally but professionally too. But could they survive, would they see what they had and fight to make it work?This is a couple that you will root for, they came across as normal, the flirtatious banter, the humour and the attitude, it all made them ultimately relatable.", user_id: user4.id, book_id: book161.id })
book162 = Book.create({ title: "Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire", author: "J.K. Rowling", image_url: "https://res.cloudinary.com/dt72mzjpx/image/upload/book_162.jpg", publisher: "Pottermore from J.K. Rowling ", date: "December 8, 2015", description: " &#x22;'There will be three tasks, spaced throughout the school year, and they will test the champions in many different ways &#x2026; their magical prowess - their daring - their powers of deduction - and, of course, their ability to cope with danger.'&#x22;The Triwizard Tournament is to be held at Hogwarts. Only wizards who are over seventeen are allowed to enter - but that doesn't stop Harry dreaming that he will win the competition. Then at Hallowe'en, when the Goblet of Fire makes its selection, Harry is amazed to find his name is one of those that the magical cup picks out. He will face death-defying tasks, dragons and Dark wizards, but with the help of his best friends, Ron and Hermione, he might just make it through - alive!", amazon_link: "https://www.amazon.com/Harry-Potter-Goblet-Fire-Rowling-ebook/dp/B0192CTMUU", kobo_link: "https://www.kobo.com/us/en/ebook/harry-potter-and-the-half-blood-prince-6", play_link: "https://play.google.com/store/search?c=books&hl=en&q=Harry%20Potter%20and%20the%20Goblet%20of%20Fire%20J.K.%20Rowling" })
Review.create({ title: "So much better than the movie...!", rating: 5, body: "With all of the reprints of the Harry Potter series (paperback, new cover art, movie pictures, etc), we were trying to complete our collection of the original hard back books. We didn't start buying these for our collection until book #5 when the series had gained such a huge following. We were so glad we could find these individually here on Amazon to get the missing ones.The Goblet of Fire really turned up the action and intensity of the series. The first three were all fun and enjoyable as they created a magical world. However, book four seemed to be the first that introduced the overall conflict in a more direct way and was &#34;book one&#34; of the conflict with He Who Must Not Be Named that would end in The Deathly Hallows. Even if you've seen the movies, the books are deserving of a read. The cliche that the books are always better than the movies holds very true here. We hope that JK Rowling continues to write for many years and that she can create other worlds that are equally as imaginative and engaging as this one. Thanks for a great ride!", user_id: user1.id, book_id: book162.id })
Review.create({ title: "EACH BOOK IS EXPONENTIALLY BETTER! EMOTIONAL ROLLERCOASTER..TWISTS AND TURNS..MYSTERY..EXPECT THE UNEXPECTED!", rating: 5, body: "Each book gets exponentially better. Book four is grand, rich, spectacular, & brilliant. You really are getting really deep into the Harry Potter world by the end of this book. It's great that it is long because there is more room for dialogues, mystery, suspense, action, all sorts of emotions, & other surprises. Dumbledore & Sirius have really got Harry's back. The Tri-Wizard Tournament is awesome. Harry is brave & strong. Fleur Delacour is a total hottie. Clemency Po&eacute;sy plays her role in the movie version. It is magnificent how J.K. Rowling captures the accents of Madame Maxime, Fleur, Krum and of course Hagrid as always. It does give for more interesting dialogue, and makes it authentic. Expect the unexpected, your mind will be blown by the end of the book. I give this 101 out of 100 points.", user_id: user2.id, book_id: book162.id })
Review.create({ title: "but after seeing several of my kids and wife immensely enjoy these books I began to think maybe I should ...", rating: 5, body: "I wasn't caught up in the initial hype over this series, but after seeing several of my kids and wife immensely enjoy these books I began to think maybe I should read them myself.  After having attended numerous Harry Potter themed parties from such occasions as a nearby city museum's Halloween party themed around Harry Potter to a surprise birthday party for a daughter, Harry Potter has been a fun theme that has brought fun and joy to numerous social occasions with my family and friends.  I finally began reading the Harry potter book series and find them as enjoyable as many of my favorite books from childhood like the chronicles of Narnia or the castle of Llyr.  Thanks mrs Rowling for bringing such joy to me and my family and providing an excuse for a great theme to build memories around!", user_id: user3.id, book_id: book162.id })
Review.create({ title: "Do not buy Kindle version - defective", rating: 1, body: "The Kindle version is defective as some reviewers wrote (I wish I had read them before I purchased), on an iPad with Kindle app in my case.  When reading with the device held in landspace (side ways) position, the last sentence on the first column repeats at the beginning of the second column on every page.  Additionally, sections of certain sentences are missing randomly.  Oddly, this problem seems to go away when the device is held in portrait  orientation.I chatted with Amazon tech support, but after trying several fixes nothing helped and they are giving me a credit for the purchase.  They also told me that this version will not be available for purchase until the problem is fixed, but I still see it listed for purchase.  So, buyers beware.", user_id: user4.id, book_id: book162.id })
Review.create({ title: "Very disappointed by my copy.", rating: 1, body: "I was very excited to finally own a hard copy version of a Harry Potter book amd the package arrived on time and was in good condition. However, when I opened the book itself, I found that pages 333-336 were totally shredded. I was so sad at this because I wanted to start reading immediately. How can I fix this, Amazon? I live in Trinidad and Tobago.", user_id: user5.id, book_id: book162.id })
book163 = Book.create({ title: "Black: The Circle Series", author: "Ted Dekker", image_url: "https://res.cloudinary.com/dt72mzjpx/image/upload/book_163.jpg", publisher: "Thomas Nelson; 2 Anv edition ", date: "July 27, 2009", description: " An Adrenaline-Laced Epic Where Dreams and Reality Collide. Fleeing assailants through deserted alleyways, Thomas Hunter narrowly escapes to the roof of a building. Then a silent bullet from the night clips his head . . . and his world goes black. From the blackness comes an amazing reality of another world where evil is contained. A world where Thomas Hunter is in love with a beautiful woman. But then he remembers the dream of being chased through an alleyway as he reaches to touch the blood on his head. Where does the dream end and reality begin? Every time he falls asleep in one world, he awakes in the other. Yet in both, catastrophic disaster awaits him . . . may even be caused by him. Some say the world hangs in the balance of every choice we make. Now the fate of two worlds hangs in the balance of one man's choices.", amazon_link: "https://www.amazon.com/Black-Circle-Ted-Dekker-ebook/dp/B006IE800O", kobo_link: "https://www.kobo.com/us/en/search?query=Black:%20The%20Circle%20Series%20Ted%20Dekker", play_link: "https://play.google.com/store/search?c=books&hl=en&q=Black:%20The%20Circle%20Series%20Ted%20Dekker" })
Review.create({ title: "Bridging the Fantasy/Reality Gap", rating: 5, body: "", user_id: user1.id, book_id: book163.id })
Review.create({ title: "Creative, Thought-Provoking Story!", rating: 5, body: "Only my second five star review. Creative concept involving someone living in two different time periods during &#34;dreams&#34;, which turn out to be interconnected realities and not dreams. Love the theological concepts woven into the plot during the future time period, which reminded me a lot of a Garden of Eden in which God lives in close relationship to God's creation until the patriarch gives into temptation. I immediately started reading the sequel &#34;Red&#34;.", user_id: user2.id, book_id: book163.id })
Review.create({ title: "Some of the Best from Dekker", rating: 5, body: "I've read every novel Ted Dekker has written (and will continue to do so). Every time a new one comes out, I hope it'll be better than his older novels, and am slightly disappointed when they aren't. I'm sure there are people who will disagree, but I think Dekker's older novels (Circle Trilogy, Martyr's Song Trilogy, Thr3e & Obsessed) are the best he's written. Don't get me wrong: I like all of Dekker's novels, but my favorites are his older ones. I bought the Circle Trilogy a few years ago, read it, then sold it to fund my voratious book reading habit. Recently I regretted selling them, and just purchased another set that I will NEVER sell! Dekker's next novels - a six series set, is loosely tied to the Circle Trilogy, and so I'll be reading them again before his next books come out in February 2008.Buy the Circle Trilogy and enjoy some of the best Dekker has ever written.", user_id: user3.id, book_id: book163.id })
Review.create({ title: "Riveting", rating: 5, body: "Ted Decker has a way of drawing you into his own story and reality through a staggering and exciting narrative. Ted writes with a imagination unbound by world standards or exercises. Wonderful book!", user_id: user4.id, book_id: book163.id })
Review.create({ title: "An amazing picture of Gods love for us!", rating: 5, body: "I had a bit of a hard time getting into the book at the beginning with the jumps from world to world (I'm not THAT fond of sci-fi) but once I adapted to the story line and crossover to the other world, this book (and the ones that follow) really grabbed me! I love the way Dekker paints a picture of Gods amazing love for us. That God would love after the betrayal and denial is so amazing and such a difficult concept. We typically try to put God into a human box and if God was like us, by the time we come around to even looking into who He really is, we'd have blown it past any hope of redemption. But these books really show you in a powerful way that God is not to be boxed into our human frame. He may be a lion, a lamb or a boy... And that our sin really hurts God but that He makes a way. Definitely a 5 star story.", user_id: user5.id, book_id: book163.id })
Review.create({ title: "IMMATURE", rating: 1, body: "I am glad that I finally finished this first book. I will not finish the series. The premise is intriguing, but the writing is simply weak.  I feel like it was written for junior high students. I would not waste time with this book.", user_id: user6.id, book_id: book163.id })
book165 = Book.create({ title: "The Atlantis Plague: A Thriller (The Origin Mystery, Book 2)", author: "A.G. Riddle", image_url: "https://res.cloudinary.com/dt72mzjpx/image/upload/book_165.jpg", publisher: "Riddle Inc.; 1 edition ", date: "November 16, 2013", description: " The Atlantis Plague is the second book in The Origin Mystery, the trilogy that has become a global phenomenon.                 * Over 2,000,000 copies sold * Translated into 23 languages * In development to be a major motion picture *NOTE: All three books in the Atlantis trilogy are now available.                 __________________________________________________________________A PANDEMIC 70,000 YEARS IN THE MAKING...WILL CHANGE HUMANITY...FOREVER.__________________________________________________________________In Marbella, Spain, Dr. Kate Warner awakens to a horrifying reality: the human race stands on the brink of extinction. A pandemic unlike any before it has swept the globe. Nearly a billion people are dead--and those that the Atlantis Plague does not kill, it transforms at the genetic level. A few rapidly evolve. The remainder devolve.As the world slips into chaos, radical solutions emerge. Industrialized nations offer a miracle drug, Orchid, which they mass produce and distribute to refugee camps around the world. But Orchid is merely a way to buy time. It treats the symptoms of the plague but never cures the disease.Immari International offers a different approach: do nothing. Let the plague run its course. The Immari envision a world populated by the genetically superior survivors--a new human race, ready to fulfill its destiny.With control of the world population hanging in the balance, the Orchid Alliance and the Immari descend into open warfare. Now the last hope for humanity is to find a cure. Kate alone holds the key to unraveling the mystery surrounding the Atlantis Plague. The answer may lie in understanding pivotal events in human history--events when the human genome mysteriously changed. Her journey takes her across the barren wastelands of Europe and northern Africa, but it is her research into the past that takes her where she never expected to go. She soon discovers that the history of human evolution is not what it seems--and setting it right may require a sacrifice she never imagined.__________________________________________________________________&#x22;The human race must remain as one. All other roads lead to ruin.&#x22;- The Orchid Alliance&#x22;Evolution is inevitable. Only fools fight fate.&#x22;- Immari International__________________________________________________________________ABOUT:THE ATLANTIS PLAGUE is a story of human survival and perseverance in the face of extinction. This global adventure takes readers back into the world of The Origin Mystery, which began with THE ATLANTIS GENE. THE ATLANTIS PLAGUE delivers the same kind of little-known science and history readers applauded in THE ATLANTIS GENE and deepens the core mystery so many readers are talking about. The series is currently in development to be a major motion picture.All three books in the trilogy are now available:Book 1: The Atlantis Gene -- amazon.com/dp/B00C2WDD5IBook 2: The Atlantis Plague -- amazon.com/dp/B00GR5JZHQBook 3: The Atlantis World -- amazon.com/dp/B00JVUQ2H0", amazon_link: "https://www.amazon.com/Atlantis-Plague-Thriller-Origin-Mystery-ebook/dp/B00GR5JZHQ", kobo_link: "https://www.kobo.com/us/en/search?query=The%20Atlantis%20Plague:%20A%20Thriller%20(The%20Origin%20Mystery,%20Book%202)%20A.G.%20Riddle", play_link: "https://play.google.com/store/search?c=books&hl=en&q=The%20Atlantis%20Plague:%20A%20Thriller%20(The%20Origin%20Mystery,%20Book%202)%20A.G.%20Riddle" })
Review.create({ title: "Wonderful Sequel!", rating: 5, body: "I loved the story from the first book, but I struggled with the writing style and character development.  This sequel expands the original story, ties up some loose ends, and the best surprise for me was how much better the character development was.  The book can get fairly technical sometimes, but I like that kind of science fiction.  Some of the tangents can get annoying, and the extent of the fantastical twists gets fairly complex.  Ultimately, I was able to follow along enough to really dig the technical stuff and care about the characters.  The story touches on so many facets of the human experience: science, religion, history, evolution, biology, physics, good vs. evil.  I highly recommend reading the first book, and jumping right into this one.Just like the first one, I borrowed the book from the Kindle Lending library, and then decided to support the author and buy a copy after the fact.  Great stuff, keep it coming!", user_id: user1.id, book_id: book165.id })
Review.create({ title: "Expected More", rating: 2, body: "I liked the first book in this series and was excited about reading this, but I was disappointed to say the least. The book started out good and quickly went down hill. There seemed to be too many things going on, and switching from the past to the present and adding all the different names of the characters along with the many different places things were happening....it all got confusing.  I found myself getting bored towards the middle and couldn't wait to finish it just so I could start to read something else. If you like keeping up with a bunch of things at one time then this book is for you.", user_id: user2.id, book_id: book165.id })
Review.create({ title: "Super story telling", rating: 5, body: "I read this and&nbsp;After Days (The After Days Trilogy)&nbsp;by Scott Medbury, one after the other in three nights, they are both so good its amazing. If you love fast paced writing and unputdownable stories i give both a huge thumbs up...Atlantis Plague is a great follow up to the Gene and Mr Riddle keeps the action coming. It really was unputdownable and I so hope they decide to make the whole series into a movie or a HBO series. Don't miss it!", user_id: user3.id, book_id: book165.id })
Review.create({ title: "Fantastic sequel!", rating: 5, body: "If you haven't read book one of this series, you need to do so immediately.  The follow-up second book is just as good - perhaps even better than the first.  Well developed characters, stunning plot twists, history, genetics, science fiction - its all here.  Believe me, you won't be able to put it down.", user_id: user4.id, book_id: book165.id })
Review.create({ title: "Ugh.. Reasons why I found this book infuriating.", rating: 2, body: "So, like many others, I read the first book and thought it was pretty good, and seeing the higher overall Amazon rating, I went ahead and bought the second.  I immediately added on the Audible 'whisper sync' for it, as I listen to books on my walk to and from class (so about an hour each day).  Normally, I love listening to books, as it draws you in, and makes my walk go by really quickly.  As a result, I can forgive quite a bit, since it's largely to fill in this walking time in an enjoyable fashion.  However...Never have I been so fed up with a book!  The first fifth of the book I was okay with, the exposition was a bit excessive (and could have been handled better, as it came across a bit condescending to the reader), but I was willing to look past that.  After that, it became increasing infuriating (I'll get to why in a moment), and I found myself rolling my eyes, and muttering 'ugh' and sighing to myself, as the narrator droned on (doing the best with what he was given).  I probably looked crazy.. I ended up turning it off halfway through, and have since switched to re-listening to the Silo series (fantastic by the way), as I'd rather repeat a good book, than listen to this one.  Which is saying a LOT since I even allowed myself to zone out during this book, and even that couldn't make it tolerable.Okay, now for reasons I can think of at the moment..**The dialogue.. oh god, the dialogue.  Enough said.**The characters are either ridiculously dense, or incredibly clever.  It's as though they were given lists of prerequisite skills/knowledge before embarking on this journey--in that each seems to know exactly the right information on cue as needed.**The amount of times a character says &#34;I don't understand&#34;, or something synonymous, deserves a tally of its own (hey, make it a drinking game! by the end you will have the same ability to put together pieces of the puzzle as the characters!).**No one dies!!! And I don't mean the character's random abilities to come back to life (which seem to come and go)--I will look past that even.  There are so many ridiculous, dangerous situations they walk straight into, and no one dies! Authors really need to not be afraid of killing off a main character for the sake of a more realistic story.  I really should have counted how many times a character was in a situation where they should have been killed, but somehow, miraculously, escaped the scenario.  Hell, when Martin died (spoiler alert) I was about 75% convinced that he would not stay dead.**The uniqueness granted to Kate became annoying.  By that I mean the amount everything revolves around her becomes a bit much. Again, I know she's the lead, but still.**Along that line, the scenarios are just beyond suspension of disbelief.  I know, I know, it's fiction and adventure/sci-fi-ish, but even for the genre, the plot pushes the limits.  Oddly enough, the scenarios become repetitive, like an episode of House, or Bones, where you kinda know the overall arc of each episode before it starts.  As a result, each dangerous scenario becomes boring, because you already know how it's going to end up.**The characters are unlikeable.  I struggled to even find one that I didn't mind and maybe even liked.  Which is really annoying.  I tried, I really did, but just couldn't.  Oh, maybe Naomi, she seemed pretty cool.  (too bad she was only around for fifty pages or so).  Ooh, and that random guy who was in the trial in China--the backstory about his impoverished family and him moving to the city to find work was rather interesting.**The 'relationship' between Kate and David is just annoying, and poorly done.  The physicality between the two also was written from a man's unrealistic perspective (like, I'm sorry, but after an incredibly physically/emotionally draining escape, would they really want to hook up immediately?).**The author does seem to have done quite a bit of historical research, which deserves some credit, (I'll assume it's all mostly true), but it's given in such a way that it felt like I was back in history class--not good.**The author writes to the readers are though we are all idiots, nothing is left to be deduced and no credit is given to the reader's ability to not need every little thing spelled out as though it was geared towards 12-year olds.**The story becomes rather muddled by about a quarter of the way through.Ugh.  Yeah, so, clearly I don't recommend this book.  I would recommend the first book, but just ahead and treat it like a standalone novel, and NOT the first in a trilogy..So, the stars:  1 for the overall cost being pretty low, and 1 more because the narrater did a pretty good job. If I had managed to get to the end, I'd have added another one, just since it seems as though finishing deserves a star.. So, 2/5", user_id: user5.id, book_id: book165.id })
Review.create({ title: "Great sequel!", rating: 5, body: "Ties history, anthropology, physics and sci-fi together in a very believable scenario. I loved that I couldn't figure out who the actual bad guys were until you wanted me to know... Good sequel to a very intriguing plot given todays medical interest in gene splicing using viruses to insert them specifically where they are needed, etc., ties most everything together from the first book, but leaves openings for more books to come... keep them coming!", user_id: user6.id, book_id: book165.id })
Review.create({ title: "Wonderful and complex!", rating: 5, body: "I have thoroughly enjoyed reading both The Atlantis Gene and Plague, and eagerly await the next installation. The story is quite exciting, and most definitely qualifies as an edge of your seat thriller, but is also quite complex and requires frequent stops to ponder the theories. I did get lost a couple of times, but I just had to read on and was rewarded with some resolution - although I have concluded that I am definitely not smart enough to be an Atlantean - and could quite possibly be one of the devolving! Thank you, Mr. Riddle, for writing an intelligent and highly entertaining series, and I very much look forward to your next release.", user_id: user7.id, book_id: book165.id })
Review.create({ title: "Don't waste your time", rating: 1, body: "This is a totally disorganized mess.  The plot and it's engine to carry it are without question utterly incomprehensible. Nothing follows reason and the author doesn't seem to care that the story bogs down and then makes a 180 in a totally unconnected way. The science may be authentic but it's incorporation into a rational plot never comes along. The author's need to question morality or it's meaning is lost in a confused cloud that makes the reader weary, not allowing any sympathy for either the characters or the story.There are so many other stories out there to read, I am truly sorry I wasted my time on this one.", user_id: user8.id, book_id: book165.id })
book167 = Book.create({ title: "Family Tree: A Novel", author: "Susan Wiggs", image_url: "https://res.cloudinary.com/dt72mzjpx/image/upload/book_167.jpg", publisher: "William Morrow ", date: "August 9, 2016", description: " From the #1 New York Times bestselling author comes a powerful, emotionally complex story of love, loss, the pain of the past&#8212;and the promise of the future.Sometimes the greatest dream starts with the smallest element. A single cell, joining with another. And then dividing. And just like that, the world changes. Annie Harlow knows how lucky she is. The producer of a popular television cooking show, she loves her handsome husband and the beautiful Los Angeles home they share. And now, she&#8217;s pregnant with their first child. But in an instant, her life is shattered. And when Annie awakes from a yearlong coma, she discovers that time isn&#8217;t the only thing she&#8217;s lost.Grieving and wounded, Annie retreats to her old family home in Switchback, Vermont, a maple farm generations old. There, surrounded by her free-spirited brother, their divorced mother, and four young nieces and nephews, Annie slowly emerges into a world she left behind years ago: the town where she grew up, the people she knew before, the high-school boyfriend turned judge. And with the discovery of a cookbook her grandmother wrote in the distant past, Annie unearths an age-old mystery that might prove the salvation of the family farm.Family Tree is the story of one woman&#8217;s triumph over betrayal, and how she eventually comes to terms with her past. It is the story of joys unrealized and opportunities regained. Complex, clear-eyed and big-hearted, funny, sad, and wise, it is a novel to cherish and to remember.&#160;", amazon_link: "https://www.amazon.com/Family-Tree-Novel-Susan-Wiggs-ebook/dp/B01825C50W", kobo_link: "https://www.kobo.com/us/en/search?query=Family%20Tree:%20A%20Novel%20Susan%20Wiggs", play_link: "https://play.google.com/store/search?c=books&hl=en&q=Family%20Tree:%20A%20Novel%20Susan%20Wiggs" })
